The '''red ball jett organ''',<ref name="Card Trader">{{SWCT|set=Base Series 1|cardname=Max Rebo - Band Leader}}</ref> also known as the '''red ball organ'''<ref name="Max Rebo Old">{{Databank|max-rebo|Max Rebo|oldversion=20150326234508}}</ref> or '''nalargon''',<ref name="Festival">''[[Fortnite Festival]]''</ref> was a keyboard instrument known as the signature instrument of [[Maximilian Rebo]].<ref name="Max Rebo" /> The instrument featured 21 keys<ref name="Absolutely Everything You Need to Know">''[[Star Wars: Absolutely Everything You Need to Know]]''</ref> and was able to store tracks and sound recordings.<ref name="100 Objects" />

{{Music-stub}}

==Behind the scenes==
[[File:NalargonKeytar-FortniteFestival.png|215px|thumb|right|Nalargon Keytar in ''Fortnite Festival'']]
The red ball jett organ, albeit unidentified, first appeared in the theatrical film [[Star Wars: Episode VI Return of the Jedi|''Star Wars'': Episode VI ''Return of the Jedi'']],<ref name="RotJ">{{Film|VI}}</ref> which was released on [[May 25]], [[1983]].<ref name="Year by Year">''[[Star Wars Year By Year: A Visual History, Updated and Expanded Edition]]''</ref> The instrument was later identified as red ball jett organ in a [[2015]] [[Topps]] collectible card.<ref name="Card Trader" /> The [[Databank (2014-)|Databank]] on [[StarWars.com]] identified the instrument as red ball organ,<ref name="Max Rebo Old" /> though it was later updated to have the full name.<ref name="Max Rebo" />

During a collaboration with the [[Star Wars video games|video game]] ''[[Fortnite]]'' in [[2024]], the red ball jett organ was added to ''[[Fortnite Festival]]'' as a [[:w:c:fortnite:Keytars|Keytar]] cosmetic item, with the actual musical instrument appearing in a time-limited ''Star Wars''-themed map of the Jam Stage. ''Fortnite'' identified the instrument as Nalargon;<ref name="Fortnite">{{Fortnite|url=news/star-wars-lands-in-the-fortnite-universe-the-eve-of-star-wars-day|text=Star Wars Lands in the Fortnite Universe the Eve of Star Wars Day!|date=2024-05-01}}</ref> however, the [[canon]]icity of the identification introduced in the game is unclear.<ref name="Pablo">{{Bluesky|infinata.bsky.social|post/3ktusvamkzk2t|[[Pablo Hidalgo]]|date=2024-06-01|quote=I don't really know what's up in games, but my *guess*is the name was changed to fit Fortnite brand standards and audience. I suppose an organization as big as the Empire and setting as big as a galaxy has plenty of alternate names we never hear of, and some we do.|archivefile=File:FortnitePablo-Bluesky.png}} {{C|In response to: @infinata.bsky.social Hey Pablo! Not sure if this is something you can answer, but I was wondering if Star Wars identifications or terms introduced in Fortnite can be considered canonical similar to Lego or Minecraft. For example, the death troopers were identified as AWR Troopers in the game.}}</ref> [[Leland Chee]] later clarified that there are no hard and defined rules against identifications from ''Fortnite'', deeming it safe to consider as canon.<ref name="Leland">{{Bluesky|holocronkeeper.bsky.social|post/3lcvactices2p|[[Leland Chee]]|date=2024-12-09|quote=Could you call Max Rebo's organ a narlagon? Sure. Could we include a narlagon in other content for if someone really wanted to? Sure. Would we call it a narlagon keytar? Maybe? There's no hard and fast rules for this stuff.|archiveurl=https://archive.ph/kNvgB|archivefile=File:LelandChee-FortniteID-Bluesky.png}} {{C|In response to: @holocronkeeper.bsky.social Hey, Leland. I was wondering if you are able to tell us the canonicity of names introduced in Fortnite. The term "Nalargon," for example, has not been used since the canon reset. I've seen you talked about Fortnite before, so I thought you might have an answer.}}</ref>

